Nay, how stand together these two doctrines of theirs? That the King should not bee an Officer of the Kingdome of Christ: but the Officer of the Father: and yet as they subscribe, bee supreame Gouernour in the Church, which is not the kingdome of the Father, as they say, but the kingdome of the sonne Christ? Can the king bee the Gouernour of the Church, which is the Kingdome of Christ, as they subscribe: and yet be no officer of the Church, as they teach? Is a Gouernour of the Church, no Officer of the Church? can the king be the Vice-roy of the father, whose kingdome the Church is not, as they teach, and yet gouerne the kingdome of Christ; which is not the kingdome, as they say, of the father, but of the son;
and yet be no officer of the kingdome of the sonne Christ neither? can the Chauncellour of king Iames, our Soueraigne Lord, be the Chauncellour of the Romane Empire, and yet not deputed to that office by the Emperour? or can the Chauncellour of England, be the Chauncellour of Spaine, and yet not substituted by the king of Spaine? or can the Vice-roy of Spaine, bee the Vicegerent of the king of England, and yet not receiue this office, and power from the king of England? Fie, what stuffe is here? what trash, what hay and stubble is heere, built vpon the foundation of gold? or what (to reconcile these their contrarieties) shall we say, that the father is supreame Gouernour ouer common-weales, and that the king is his substitute to gouerne that: and that the sonne is supreame gouernour ouer Churches, and that the king is his Deputie also for him to gouerne that? Indeed thus we shall reconcile them: but then we shall vndoe them▪ for this distinction then will do them no good. For it will not except (as faine by this they would) the king, from being an officer of the Church of Christ, it will vtterly cast downe that their strong hold, that holdeth the Ministers, & the Elders, to be the only Church officers: & thus, either, their doctrine must be contrary to their subscription: or if these disagree not, they must confesse, that kings, & princes, be aswell the officers of the Church, as the Ministers, or lay Elders be: and that they must rule it as well with their sword, as the Elders with their sword: & therfore, that the Church may aswell be gouerned by the ciuill sword, without the Ecclesiasticall: as it was once gouerned by the Ecclesiasticall, without the ciuill. Yea if we shall thus reconcile them, they must be driuen to confesse, that this their distinction, is friuolous, and therfore cast it away, as a vaine one, which neither doth them any good, nor our cause any harme at all, only it seperateth, and diuideth, the father, & the son, in their raigne, & kingdome: & disioineth them asunder, like two earthly kings; hauing either of them one kingdome seuerall to himselfe: the one sharing the Church for his kingdome, and the other sharing Common-weales for his kingdome. Yea it distracteth vs, for it teacheth vs, that we are not all subiects vnto one king, which is Christ: nor all to one God, which is the father: some be the subiects of the father, and some of vs bee the subiects of the sonne: those of the commonweale, are the subiects of the father, and those of the Church, are the subiects of Christ. (Now I pray you whither bee greater the
people of the Common-weale, that be the subiects of the father: or the people of the Chur • h, that be the subiects of Christ?) And no maruell if this doctrine of diuision, (which dooth not subordaine the one, vnder the other; the sonne vnder the father: but doth deuide in two the kingdomes, and the kings of heauen) doe make diuision, and deuide asunder the kings and the people of the earth.
